00:19:59.820 --> 00:20:05.480
So rich basically formats data in a very pleasing to the eye way.

00:20:06.840 --> 00:20:13.780
You can print say a Python dict and it'll format with an indentation and it'll colorize strings

00:20:13.980 --> 00:20:14.260
and things.

00:20:15.780 --> 00:20:22.800
And you can print things like tables quite effortlessly, syntax highlighted code, and

00:20:22.940 --> 00:20:26.000
you can use up to 16.7 million colors.

00:20:27.120 --> 00:20:27.240
Wow.

00:20:27.240 --> 00:20:34.540
Essentially it was a toolkit to prettify terminal output with as little effort as possible.

00:20:35.480 --> 00:20:38.580
And it's all kind of integrated.

00:20:39.420 --> 00:20:46.480
So you can put syntax-highlighted text inside a table or a progress bar inside a cell.

00:20:46.660 --> 00:20:48.480
And everything kind of works together.

00:20:48.540 --> 00:20:50.960
So it's a single coherent system.

00:20:51.040 --> 00:20:53.900
Because some of this stuff existed prior to Rich.

00:20:54.780 --> 00:20:56.500
But they were written by different authors.

00:20:57.340 --> 00:20:59.020
And they weren't designed to work together.

00:20:59.900 --> 00:21:06.540
Maybe there's a table one by one person and then a progress bar by another.

00:21:06.600 --> 00:21:09.220
And they didn't really work the same or integrate or things like that.

00:21:09.280 --> 00:21:11.200
Yeah, exactly. Exactly.

00:21:11.460 --> 00:21:17.180
So it meant that terminal output was still quite basic.

00:21:17.940 --> 00:21:22.800
When color was used, it would colorize a single line or something like that.

00:21:23.440 --> 00:21:30.140
And it still it helped, but it wasn't great for parsing visually

00:21:30.320 --> 00:21:31.060
parsing that information.

00:21:32.200 --> 00:21:36.640
But Rich gave you that ability that when you write output, it is readable.

00:21:38.360 --> 00:21:45.320
I think prior to that, we developers kind of built up this skill of staring at monochrome

00:21:46.020 --> 00:21:52.080
text with funny characters and numbers and somehow pulling out meaningful information

00:21:52.940 --> 00:21:53.340
out of that.

00:21:53.340 --> 00:21:59.840
And it took years to develop, but hopefully now we don't need to, you know, because you

00:21:59.940 --> 00:22:04.580
can write things to the terminal that looks much like the output you'd get in a browser.

00:22:05.100 --> 00:22:08.040
It's formatted and readable and colourful.

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:14.020
Yeah. You know, one thing that might be worth talking about is the live updates.

00:22:16.240 --> 00:22:17.560
Like live tables and stuff.

00:22:18.720 --> 00:22:25.180
Yes. So in RIT you can create a live object. That's what the class is called.

00:22:25.380 --> 00:22:31.780
And basically it clears the screen and it writes that output and then you can refresh it.

00:22:32.580 --> 00:22:39.480
It can do that quickly, like 20 times a second or less, depending on how much data you've

00:22:39.480 --> 00:22:39.520
got.

00:22:39.560 --> 00:22:46.680
So you can create animations, you can create dashboards, you can create like a scrolling

00:22:46.900 --> 00:22:48.420
list of text.

00:22:51.220 --> 00:22:52.800
But it was kind of, it was limited.

00:22:53.860 --> 00:22:57.260
All it could do is update information regularly.

00:22:57.260 --> 00:22:58.060
It wasn't interactive.

00:22:59.260 --> 00:23:04.260
couldn't click or scroll or even detect key presses.

00:23:04.450 --> 00:23:07.000
It was purely for updating information.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:11.700
It's like a very rudimentary predecessor of textual.

