Yeah, I think so too.

01:04:52.010 --> 01:04:52.640
A bit further down.

01:04:54.579 --> 01:05:00.520
So one of the problems we had in textual, when interfaces get complex, we've got lots and lots of widgets.

01:05:01.480 --> 01:05:04.440
Some of them are visible and some of them are not. Some of them are scrolled off.

01:05:05.119 --> 01:05:07.480
They're still there in memory. We know exactly where they are.

01:05:09.490 --> 01:05:13.560
And when we come to render that, the most obvious way to do that is to step through them in a for loop,

01:05:14.320 --> 01:05:17.580
for widgets in all widgets, do stuff to widget.

01:05:19.180 --> 01:05:26.640
So that means we're iterating over all the widgets every single time, even if they aren't visible.

01:05:28.420 --> 01:05:31.040
So the spatial map is an attempt to optimize that.

01:05:31.100 --> 01:05:37.740
Basically it's a very quick way of deciding which the widgets are on screen and which the widgets are currently scrolled off.

01:05:38.720 --> 01:05:41.740
So we literally don't need to even loop through the scrolled off widgets.

01:05:42.920 --> 01:05:50.900
And the way we did that briefly is we kind of logically separated the terminal into a grid.

01:05:52.140 --> 01:05:59.220
There's a step where you go through and assign every widget to the grid squares that it might overlap with.

01:05:59.770 --> 01:06:02.300
Small widgets might be right inside a grid square.

01:06:03.130 --> 01:06:05.780
Some may overlap one or two or more.

01:06:06.660 --> 01:06:12.020
And then once we've got that information, it's very easy to pick out which widgets are visible

01:06:12.150 --> 01:06:14.660
and exclude which widgets aren't.

01:06:15.440 --> 01:06:20.580
Because we can take the screen, figure out which of the grid squares it covers, and then

01:06:20.580 --> 01:06:24.580
we can go through those grid squares, and there's probably just a handful of them, and

01:06:24.580 --> 01:06:27.820
each of those grid squares is associated with a list of widgets which are under that.

01:06:28.870 --> 01:06:33.540
You can combine that with a set, and then very quickly you've reduced that problem domain

01:06:33.560 --> 01:06:38.000
from being potentially unbounded very large to like very small.

01:06:38.980 --> 01:06:40.780
Some of the widgets might actually not be visible.

01:06:40.850 --> 01:06:42.720
They might actually be in a grid square,

01:06:42.850 --> 01:06:44.180
which is off the edge of the screen.

01:06:45.660 --> 01:06:49.300
But we can just loop through those and discard those ones.

01:06:49.390 --> 01:06:50.800
But that's a much smaller operation

01:06:51.470 --> 01:06:53.240
than looping through every widget.

01:06:53.860 --> 01:06:54.460
Yeah, interesting.

